	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yes. But be sure to tie the unused addresses to ground

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Thu Apr 28, 2011 12:24 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />We usually fill the entire chip to reduce the chances for errors when soldering the chip, because even if you don't ground all the upper address pins the game will still work. If you have full confidence in your soldering, there's no need to fill the chip.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
